<!-- Lesson 4-1: Secure Communications -->
<div id="lesson4-1-content" class="lesson-container">
    <p class="mb-4 glowing-intro">Secure communications are essential in our digital world. Every day, billions of messages, transactions, and data transfers occur online that need protection from eavesdropping and tampering. Let's explore how cryptography makes secure communications possible.</p>
    
    <div class="key-concept mb-5 animated-concept">
        <h4><i class="fas fa-key rotating-key"></i> Key Concept</h4>
        <p>Secure communication involves protecting both the confidentiality and integrity of messages as they travel across networks. This is achieved through a layered approach using various cryptographic protocols and techniques.</p>
    </div>
    
    <div class="lesson-section mb-5">
        <h3 class="section-title">The CIA Triad in Communications</h3>
        
        <p>The security of communications is often evaluated against the CIA triadâ€”a model for information security that focuses on three key aspects:</p>
        
<div class="triad-diagram interactive-triad">
            <div class="triad-node hover-expand">
                <div class="triad-icon"><i class="fas fa-user-secret pulse-icon"></i></div>
                <h4>Confidentiality</h4>
                <p>Ensuring that information is accessible only to authorized individuals and kept hidden from others.</p>
                <div class="technique-list animated-list">
                    <span class="technique glow-badge">Encryption</span>
                    <span class="technique glow-badge">Access controls</span>
                    <span class="technique glow-badge">Authentication</span>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="triad-node hover-expand">
                <div class="triad-icon"><i class="fas fa-check-circle pulse-icon"></i></div>
                <h4>Integrity</h4>
                <p>Ensuring that information remains accurate, complete, and unaltered during transit or storage.</p>
                <div class="technique-list animated-list">
                    <span class="technique glow-badge">Hash functions</span>
                    <span class="technique glow-badge">Digital signatures</span>
                    <span class="technique glow-badge">Message authentication codes</span>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="triad-node hover-expand">
                <div class="triad-icon"><i class="fas fa-clock pulse-icon"></i></div>
                <h4>Availability</h4>
                <p>Ensuring that information and systems are available when needed by authorized users.</p>
                <div class="technique-list animated-list">
                    <span class="technique glow-badge">Redundancy</span>
                    <span class="technique glow-badge">Backup systems</span>
                    <span class="technique glow-badge">DDoS protection</span>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    
    <div class="lesson-section mb-5">
        <h3 class="section-title">Secure Communication Protocols</h3>
        
<div class="protocol-cards interactive-cards">
            <div class="protocol-card spotlight-card">
                <div class="protocol-header">
                    <h4>TLS/SSL</h4>
                    <div class="protocol-icon"><i class="fas fa-lock glow-icon"></i></div>
                </div>
                <div class="protocol-body">
                    <p><strong>Transport Layer Security</strong> (TLS) and its predecessor <strong>Secure Sockets Layer</strong> (SSL) are cryptographic protocols designed to provide secure communication over a computer network.</p>
                    
                    <div class="protocol-process">
                        <h5>How it works:</h5>
                        <ol class="animated-list">
                            <li class="highlight-step">Client and server perform a handshake to establish trust</li>
                            <li class="highlight-step">They negotiate which cipher suite (set of algorithms) to use</li>
                            <li class="highlight-step">They authenticate each other (usually server authenticates to client)</li>
                            <li class="highlight-step">They establish a shared secret key for session encryption</li>
                            <li class="highlight-step">All subsequent communications are encrypted with this key</li>
                        </ol>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="protocol-applications">
                        <h5>Common Uses:</h5>
                        <ul class="check-list">
                            <li>HTTPS (Secure Websites)</li>
                            <li>Secure Email (SMTPS, IMAPS, POP3S)</li>
                            <li>VPN connections</li>
                            <li>Online banking and e-commerce</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="protocol-footer">
                    <div class="protocol-note highlight-note">
                        <i class="fas fa-info-circle pulse-icon"></i>
                        <p>The padlock icon in your browser indicates TLS/SSL protection</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="protocol-card">
                <div class="protocol-header">
                    <h4>SSH</h4>
                    <div class="protocol-icon"><i class="fas fa-terminal"></i></div>
                </div>
                <div class="protocol-body">
                    <p><strong>Secure Shell</strong> (SSH) is a cryptographic network protocol for secure remote login and other secure network services over an unsecured network.</p>
                    
                    <div class="protocol-process">
                        <h5>How it works:</h5>
                        <ol>
                            <li>Uses public-key cryptography for authentication</li>
                            <li>Allows secure login to remote systems</li>
                            <li>Establishes encrypted tunnels for secure data transfer</li>
                            <li>Supports multiple authentication methods</li>
                            <li>Uses symmetric encryption for session data</li>
                        </ol>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="protocol-applications">
                        <h5>Common Uses:</h5>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Remote server administration</li>
                            <li>Secure file transfers (SCP, SFTP)</li>
                            <li>Port forwarding and tunneling</li>
                            <li>Remote command execution</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="protocol-footer">
                    <div class="protocol-note">
                        <i class="fas fa-info-circle"></i>
                        <p>SSH largely replaced insecure protocols like Telnet and FTP</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="protocol-card">
                <div class="protocol-header">
                    <h4>End-to-End Encryption</h4>
                    <div class="protocol-icon"><i class="fas fa-comments"></i></div>
                </div>
                <div class="protocol-body">
                    <p><strong>End-to-End Encryption</strong> (E2EE) ensures that only the communicating users can read the messages. No intermediary, not even the service provider, can access the content.</p>
                    
                    <div class="protocol-process">
                        <h5>How it works:</h5>
                        <ol>
                            <li>Encryption occurs on the sender's device</li>
                            <li>Data remains encrypted in transit</li>
                            <li>Data remains encrypted on service providers' servers</li>
                            <li>Decryption occurs only on the recipient's device</li>
                            <li>Keys never leave the end user devices</li>
                        </ol>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="protocol-applications">
                        <h5>Common Uses:</h5>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Messaging apps (Signal, WhatsApp)</li>
                            <li>Secure email services (ProtonMail)</li>
                            <li>Video conferencing (Zoom E2EE mode)</li>
                            <li>Voice calls in secure messengers</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="protocol-footer">
                    <div class="protocol-note">
                        <i class="fas fa-info-circle"></i>
                        <p>E2EE protects against service provider data breaches</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    
    <div class="lesson-section mb-5">
