<!-- Lesson 4-2: Digital Signatures -->
<div id="lesson4-2-content" class="lesson-container">
    <p class="mb-4 highlight-intro">Digital signatures are one of the most important applications of cryptography, providing a way to verify the authenticity and integrity of digital documents, messages, or software. They serve as the electronic equivalent of handwritten signatures or stamped seals, but with far greater security.</p>
    
    <div class="key-concept mb-5 enhanced-concept">
        <h4><i class="fas fa-key pulse-effect"></i> Key Concept</h4>
        <p>A digital signature is a mathematical technique used to validate the authenticity and integrity of a digital message, document, or software. It provides proof of origin, identity, and status of electronic documents, transactions, or digital messages and acknowledges informed consent by the signer.</p>
    </div>
    
    <div class="lesson-section mb-5">
        <h3 class="section-title">How Digital Signatures Work</h3>
        
        <div class="process-diagram">
            <div class="process-step">
                <div class="step-icon"><i class="fas fa-file-alt"></i></div>
                <div class="step-content">
                    <h4>1. Document Creation</h4>
                    <p>Alice creates a document that she wants to sign digitally.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="process-arrow"><i class="fas fa-arrow-down"></i></div>
            
            <div class="process-step">
                <div class="step-icon"><i class="fas fa-calculator"></i></div>
                <div class="step-content">
                    <h4>2. Hash Creation</h4>
                    <p>A hash function creates a fixed-size "fingerprint" (digest) of the document.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="process-arrow"><i class="fas fa-arrow-down"></i></div>
            
            <div class="process-step">
                <div class="step-icon"><i class="fas fa-key"></i></div>
                <div class="step-content">
                    <h4>3. Encryption with Private Key</h4>
                    <p>Alice encrypts the hash using her private key, creating the digital signature.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="process-arrow"><i class="fas fa-arrow-down"></i></div>
            
            <div class="process-step">
                <div class="step-icon"><i class="fas fa-envelope"></i></div>
                <div class="step-content">
                    <h4>4. Document Transmission</h4>
                    <p>Alice sends both the original document and the signature to Bob.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="process-arrow"><i class="fas fa-arrow-down"></i></div>
            
            <div class="process-step">
                <div class="step-icon"><i class="fas fa-unlock"></i></div>
                <div class="step-content">
                    <h4>5. Signature Verification</h4>
                    <p>Bob uses Alice's public key to decrypt the signature, obtaining the original hash.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="process-arrow"><i class="fas fa-arrow-down"></i></div>
            
            <div class="process-step">
                <div class="step-icon"><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i></div>
                <div class="step-content">
                    <h4>6. Hash Comparison</h4>
                    <p>Bob independently hashes the received document and compares it with the decrypted hash. If they match, the signature is valid.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="key-insight">
            <i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i>
            <div class="insight-content">
                <p>Digital signatures use the private key for signing (which only the signer has) and the public key for verification (which anyone can have). This is essentially the reverse of the usual encryption process, where the public key is used to encrypt and the private key to decrypt.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    
    <div class="lesson-section mb-5">
        <h3 class="section-title">What Digital Signatures Provide</h3>
        
        <div class="benefits-grid">
            <div class="benefit-item">
                <div class="benefit-icon"><i class="fas fa-user-check"></i></div>
                <h4>Authentication</h4>
                <p>Digital signatures help establish the identity of the signer. Since the signature is created using the signer's private key, which only they should possess, a valid signature provides strong evidence that the document was signed by the claimed signer.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="benefit-item">
                <div class="benefit-icon"><i class="fas fa-shield-alt"></i></div>
                <h4>Data Integrity</h4>
                <p>Any change to the document after it has been signed will invalidate the signature. This provides assurance that the content has not been altered in transit or storage.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="benefit-item">
                <div class="benefit-icon"><i class="fas fa-ban"></i></div>
                <h4>Non-repudiation</h4>
                <p>The signer cannot later deny having signed the document, as they are the only one with access to the private key used to create the signature. This provides legal accountability.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    
    <div class="lesson-section mb-5">
        <h3 class="section-title">Digital Signature Algorithms</h3>
        
        <div class="algorithm-grid">
            <div class="algorithm-card">
                <div class="algorithm-header">
                    <h4>RSA-PSS</h4>
                    <div class="algorithm-meta">
                        <span class="algorithm-type">Based on: RSA</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="algorithm-body">
                    <p>RSA Probabilistic Signature Scheme (RSA-PSS) is an improvement over the older RSA signature scheme, adding a random salt to increase security.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Based on the difficulty of factoring large numbers</li>
                        <li>Widely supported in software and hardware</li>
                        <li>Relatively slow for large files</li>
                        <li>Typical key sizes: 2048 or 4096 bits</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="algorithm-footer">
                    <div class="algorithm-status">Widely used in many applications</div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="algorithm-card">
                <div class="algorithm-header">
                    <h4>ECDSA</h4>
                    <div class="algorithm-meta">
                        <span class="algorithm-type">Based on: Elliptic Curve Cryptography</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="algorithm-body">
                    <p>Elliptic Curve Digital Signature Algorithm offers the same level of security as RSA but with smaller key sizes.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Based on the elliptic curve discrete logarithm problem</li>
                        <li>More efficient than RSA (faster, less computation)</li>
                        <li>Smaller signatures (important for space-constrained systems)</li>
                        <li>Typical key sizes: 256 or 384 bits</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="algorithm-footer">
                    <div class="algorithm-status">Popular in mobile and IoT applications</div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="algorithm-card">
                <div class="algorithm-header">
                    <h4>EdDSA</h4>
                    <div class="algorithm-meta">
                        <span class="algorithm-type">Based on: Edwards Curves</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="algorithm-body">
                    <p>Edwards-curve Digital Signature Algorithm, with Ed25519 being the most common variant, is a modern, high-security signature algorithm.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Better side-channel attack resistance than ECDSA</li>
