        <div class="blockchain-components">
            <div class="component">
                <h4>Block</h4>
                <p>The fundamental unit of a blockchain, containing:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Header:</strong> Metadata about the block</li>
                    <li><strong>Transaction Data:</strong> The actual information being stored</li>
                    <li><strong>Timestamp:</strong> When the block was created</li>
                    <li><strong>Previous Hash:</strong> Reference to the previous block</li>
                    <li><strong>Nonce:</strong> A number used once to find a valid hash</li>
                    <li><strong>Current Hash:</strong> The block's identifier, derived from all other fields</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="component">
                <h4>Cryptographic Hash</h4>
                <p>Each block contains the hash of the previous block, creating a chain. This ensures:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Any change to a block would change its hash</li>
                    <li>This would invalidate all subsequent blocks</li>
                    <li>The entire chain's integrity is maintained</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Common hash functions used: SHA-256, Keccak-256 (Ethereum)</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="component">
                <h4>Digital Signatures</h4>
                <p>Used to authorize transactions on the blockchain:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Participants have public-private key pairs</li>
                    <li>Transactions are signed with private keys</li>
                    <li>Signatures can be verified using public keys</li>
                    <li>Ensures non-repudiation and authentication</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    
    <div class="lesson-section mb-5">
        <h3 class="section-title">Consensus Mechanisms</h3>
        
        <p>Consensus mechanisms are protocols that ensure all nodes in the network agree on the state of the blockchain. They solve the "Byzantine Generals Problem" - how to reach agreement in a distributed system when some participants may be unreliable or malicious.</p>
        
        <div class="consensus-mechanisms">
            <div class="consensus-mechanism">
                <div class="mechanism-header">
                    <h4>Proof of Work (PoW)</h4>
                    <div class="mechanism-icon"><i class="fas fa-hammer"></i></div>
                </div>
                <div class="mechanism-body">
                    <p>Participants ("miners") compete to solve a computationally intensive puzzle. The first to solve it gets to add the next block to the chain and receives a reward.</p>
                    
                    <div class="mechanism-process">
                        <h5>How it works:</h5>
                        <ol>
                            <li>Miners collect pending transactions into a block</li>
                            <li>They compute a hash of the block header</li>
                            <li>They must find a nonce that makes the hash meet certain criteria (e.g., starting with a specific number of zeros)</li>
                            <li>This requires enormous computational power and trial-and-error</li>
                            <li>Once found, other nodes can easily verify the solution</li>
                        </ol>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="mechanism-examples">
                        <h5>Used in:</h5>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Bitcoin</li>
                            <li>Litecoin</li>
                            <li>Monero</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="mechanism-pros-cons">
                        <div class="pros">
                            <h5>Advantages:</h5>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Proven security track record</li>
                                <li>Highly resistant to attacks</li>
                                <li>Decentralized</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                        <div class="cons">
                            <h5>Disadvantages:</h5>
                            <ul>
                                <li>High energy consumption</li>
                                <li>Slower transaction throughput</li>
                                <li>Vulnerability to 51% attacks</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="consensus-mechanism">
                <div class="mechanism-header">
                    <h4>Proof of Stake (PoS)</h4>
                    <div class="mechanism-icon"><i class="fas fa-coins"></i></div>
                </div>
                <div class="mechanism-body">
                    <p>Validators are selected to create blocks based on the amount of cryptocurrency they hold and are willing to "stake" as collateral. If they validate fraudulent transactions, they risk losing their stake.</p>
                    
                    <div class="mechanism-process">
                        <h5>How it works:</h5>
                        <ol>
                            <li>Validators lock up some of their tokens as stake</li>
                            <li>The algorithm selects validators based on their stake</li>
                            <li>Selected validators verify and add blocks</li>
                            <li>Validators earn transaction fees as rewards</li>
                            <li>Malicious behavior results in losing part of their stake</li>
                        </ol>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="mechanism-examples">
                        <h5>Used in:</h5>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Ethereum 2.0</li>
                            <li>Cardano</li>
                            <li>Solana</li>
                            <li>Polkadot</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="mechanism-pros-cons">
                        <div class="pros">
                            <h5>Advantages:</h5>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Energy efficient</li>
                                <li>Higher transaction throughput</li>
                                <li>Lower entry barriers</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                        <div class="cons">
                            <h5>Disadvantages:</h5>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Potential for stake centralization</li>
                                <li>"Nothing at Stake" problem</li>
                                <li>Less tested than PoW</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="consensus-mechanism">
                <div class="mechanism-header">
                    <h4>Other Consensus Mechanisms</h4>
                    <div class="mechanism-icon"><i class="fas fa-cogs"></i></div>
                </div>
                <div class="mechanism-body">
                    <div class="other-mechanisms">
                        <div class="other-mechanism">
                            <h5>Delegated Proof of Stake (DPoS)</h5>
                            <p>Token holders vote for a limited number of delegates who validate transactions and create blocks. Faster, but more centralized.</p>
                            <p><strong>Examples:</strong> EOS, Tron, Cosmos</p>
                        </div>
                        
                        <div class="other-mechanism">
                            <h5>Proof of Authority (PoA)</h5>
                            <p>Transactions are validated by approved accounts (validators), who are typically known entities with reputation at stake.</p>
                            <p><strong>Examples:</strong> VeChain, POA Network, many private blockchains</p>
                        </div>
                        
                        <div class="other-mechanism">
                            <h5>Practical Byzantine Fault Tolerance (PBFT)</h5>
                            <p>Nodes vote in rounds to reach consensus, requiring a two-thirds majority. Typically used in permissioned blockchains.</p>
                            <p><strong>Examples:</strong> Hyperledger Fabric, Stellar</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
